item.title: science
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Every so often the kids will ask if a day can be a certain theme... sometimes they ask for the day to be "stay-in-your-pajamas-day", other times they'll say "can today be pirate day?". Over vacation they asked for a pirate day, which we reenacted with me playing the role of Captain Hook. I especially loved the hook for my hand! For the most part their requests are pretty simple and with a little thinking we can pull something together in no time. Today, the kids declared it to be science day! I usually pick the activities and Mark leads the lessons. It's a perfect pairing! We started science day out with a hike. We explored the trees and the rocks. We talked about erosion, the difference between a solid, liquid and a gas and practiced identifying poison oak. Then it was back home for lunch and a few experiments. The first one, the good-ole diet coke and mentos explosion. Matilda was very excited for this one! Mark was impressed with his mad-science skills! Next up, blowing up a ballon with vinegar and baking soda and poking sharp pencils through bags of water. Will the water squirt out?!!! What a great day - a lot of fun and some education mixed in the middle, love it!!!

item.title: d.a.d
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Mitch really wanted to get Mark a specific gift for his birthday. Over the last few days I let Mitch order his specific wish for his Dad. Boy, he was thrilled. This was the scene last night at dinner. Mitch: "Hey, Mom. When is (start spelling) D.A.D, (pointing to his Seahawks jersey, lifting the jersey shoulders up), coming?" Me: Mouth drops in shock. Mark: Sitting right next to Mitch turns, smiling. Me: Holding my finger over my lips to tell Mitch to keep quiet. Mitch: Wide eyed, just realized what just happened. Tears start to flow down his cheek. Mark: "Why are you crying?" Mitch: "You know now." Mark: "Know what?" Me: "Oh, you know we were wondering when you were coming back to the table." Mitch: Smiling. "Yeah, (starting to laugh) we wondered when you were coming back to the table" Mark: "Oh." Mitch & Me: Big sigh of relief... Whew, dodge that birthday secret from sneaking out of the bag! ;)

item.title: st marys basketball
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Saturday was a big game for the St Mary's mens basketball team. This week was the start of the West Coast Conference games. Mitch was super excited to be going to another game and Matilda was super excited to get to cheer on the court with the cheerleaders! Before last weeks game we were given a flyer offering a cheer camp for girls. The camp included a two hour camp to learn the fight song, a t-shirt and two tickets to the next game. As I read the flyer to Matilda I asked her if this was something she'd be interested in doing. Her first question was "will I be on TV"? "Well, there will be a TV crew there so I'd imagine you'd make it on at some point", I said. From there a smile wrapped her face and was committed! The day of the game Matilda met up with the cheerleaders an hour before to get ready. The gave her a shirt and put a St Mary's tattoo on her cheek. We all waited in the stands wondering when we'd get to see her. As the teams were warming up we saw the cheerleaders come in from the side and make their way on to the court. And there she was, my little girl, so proud of herself and her pompoms, wearing a HUGE smile! And then she got her wish, she made it on TV with an extreme close-up!!! Matilda cheered from the sidelines during the game and got up with the girls to perform their routines for timeouts. Over the course of the game Matilda started picking up the moves and really got into it! Mitchell was Matilda's biggest fan. He often would look over to see if Matilda was cheering or clapping after a score was made. At half time Matilda came to see us and Mitch was so excited to tell her what a great job she was doing! This was a very fun opportunity for Matilda. We received many comments from the crowd on how great Matilda did. I was surprised by Matilda's bravery. She didn't mind that hundreds of people were watching her or that a camera was in her face. She loved every minute of it!

item.content:encoded: My sister was very sweet and offered to host a SuperBowl party. Mitch loves the Seahawks so this day couldn't come soon enough. I don't think he's slept the last few nights, playing out in his mind each play. At the end of the game, when the Seahawks took home the win he stood, front and center, staring at the TV. Mitch couldn't be more proud of his most favorite football team... Congrats Seahawks!!!

item.title: happy birthday mitchell
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Today you turn 7. I usually start out these birthday messages with something I reflect on when I think about the last year and the year ahead. This year when I typed your age, I realized how close you are to 10. And then came the tears. You are growing way to fast for this Mama. This is my third try in finishing this note, lets see if I can make it through! Dad looks forward to these messages each year. He watches from afar and sets his clock to see how long it takes for the eyes to well up with tears and the flood gates to open. Every year Dad places a bet to see if the tears start to pour sooner or later than they did the year before. This last year you yourself have become very aware with my "Mom-tears" and will turn to Dad and whisper, "oh geeze, Mom's crying happy tears again". It's beginning to be quite the joke between the two of you and as you grow older it becomes harder and harder to hold back the tears. Most are happy tears, so proud of the big boy you are becoming, and some are tears of laughter. In the last year you have developed quite the sense of humor. You pick up on subtle sarcasm and have begun to create your own jokes. Your latest joke has been, "why didn't the nose make it on the team? Because he wasn't picked." Your love for football and your love for the Seahawks runs deeps. Living in California over the last year during one of the strongest seasons for the Seahawks, you have developed quite a thick skin for taunting. Kids and school make comments about your team, people on the streets make comments. But each day you wear your colors proudly and say, "lets see who wins, then see who's talking then." I guess the SuperBowl win for the Seahawks this year says it all now! I never knew when you came into my life that I'd be woken up each morning with a discussion about football. It's a little much for my sleepy brain in the morning but I've learned I need to be on my A-game at all times! Just following the Christmas break, three of your friends received Seahawks jerseys. Dad and I were shocked at your ability to align your friends to your affiliations. We also wondered how favorable we were in those families if they happened to be 49er fans as well!!! Everything you say, connects back to sports. The other day your Dad told you he thinks you are obsessed. When he explained what that meant he told you you eat, sleep and breath sports! And boy is your Dad right. You are competitive. Everything you do, is a competition. This trait is the laser focus you aligned your heart with to reach your goals and always strive to do your best. This trait coupled with lots of tears also provides your Dad and I plenty of opportunities to chat with you about winning and losing, or "learning" as we like to call it. We are all still growing together and learning A LOT together! You and your Dad have quite a special bond. A relationship that gets deeper each day. You call your Dad Buck-Tuck and he calls you his Buckie. For your Dad's birthday this year you asked if you could get him a new Seahawk's jersey so you could be twins. You look for your Dad in the morning when you wake up and ask for him to be the last person to say good night to you before bed. You try hard to do the right thing in your Dad's eyes and hate it when he's upset with you. A day doesn't go by without your Dad telling me, "I love that little boy" and I think the feelings are mutual from you with your Dad. You love your sister. You smother her every morning which drives her crazy. You are kind, gentle and try to share everything you know with her. Sometimes your Sister doesn't seem interested or says she doesn't want you to help her but deep down she loves all the attention you give her. When you aren't around she's asks every five minutes when we can go get you. When you are doing something she wants to know what it is. When she asks for something, she wants you to have the same. Don't let go of that sweet heart of yours and your love for your Sister. You are very special and she is very lucky to have you in her life. Mitchell, you are truly a wonderful boy. You melt my heart everyday with the things you say and do. My most favorite times are those mornings, when the sun is just starting to rise and I feel a little tap on my shoulder. I open my eyes and see the most wonderful blue eyed boy with a smile brighter than the sun. You wave and then crawl under the covers next to me. For a short while, all is quite. And then the football talk begins! :) I hope seven years old is a great year for you. Maybe after this year we can agree that you'll stop growing and begin celebrating your birthday backwards from here on out, happy 6th next year maybe?! Happy Birthday to the BEST 7 year old on the planet. Your Dad, Sister, Molly and I love you very much. XOXOXOX

item.title: Leprechauns
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: We have been working very hard preparing for the arrival of the Leprechaun's. Every year, the Leprechauns pay a visit to our house on St Patrick's Day. The kids enjoy the visits but Mark and I aren't huge fans. When the little Leprechauns they always make a complete mess while dropping off a few treats for the kids. The treats we like, the mess, not so much. So, this year we're making plans to set out a trap in an attempt to catch a few Leprechauns. Once we catch them we want to chat with them about their mischief. Matilda has been very serious about this task and has been talking non-stop about her trap-plans. The other day, she outlined her plans and walked us through her Leprechaun-catching process. Then we started to build Matilda's ideas into a trap. We had all the supplies... glue, glitter, gold coins, scissors! The Leprechauns climb up the latter on the side, walk across the top and then fall in from our trap door. Our Leprechaun catcher is amazing, there is no way these Leprechauns are getting away this year!!!

item.title: Pool time
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: The temps have started to slowly creep up this week and so have the requests from the kids to open the pool. Mark checked the pool temperature yesterday and it was 71 degrees. As a surprise before the kids got home from school, Mark added a little warmth to the hot tub so they could swim. But when the kids got home and were told they could swim, they wanted in to the pool and were off the diving board in no time! When the sun started to go down we had to pull the kids out of the water. They loved it and can't wait for summer to arrive!!! PS. We were looking back at the blog last year to see when we started swimming. Funny enough, the first swim of the year was March 13, 2013. Exactly one year ago today!!!

item.title: st patricks day unfolded
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: The night before the little Leprechaun's were to arrive Mark, was out with the kids building more traps. The kids wanted to be extra prepared this year and put one trap at every door! Mitch's trap had a platform to walk up with one piece of thin tissue paper stretched tightly across the top. When the weight of the Lephrechaun walked across the paper, they'd fall through and get stuck inside with the double sided tape lining the bottom of the box! Matilda's trap had a trip-wire on the edge of a box with gold inside to coax the Leprechaun's into the trap. The minute they hit the trip wire, crash the lid would close and the tiny little green people would be stuck inside! The next morning the kids sprang out of bed in search of a Leprechaun in our traps. Matilda said in the middle of the night she heard a door shut. So the kids went to check all the traps. To our surprise, we caught a Leprechaun shoe! Woah, our traps worked! We might not have caught a Leprechaun but we caught their shoes which meant that we are bound to get them next year!!! The kids searched the rest of the house to see if there were any other traces of the Leprechaun's. There were green four leaf clovers leading them into the garage. But, as soon as the kids opened the door a big piece of Styrofoam came crashing down from the door way (see above the door in the photo!). When the kids made it safely into the garage to their surprise the Leprechaun, Larry left a note saying "hee, hee can't catch me"! Larry then set up a human trap to try to catch them and put a box of Lucy Charms inside to try to coax them in! Matilda did not like when the trap came down on her at all! One our way back inside we found, in addition to underwear hanging from the lights, that the Leprechaun's had blocked the doorway to their playroom with the sofa cushions and played with their toys. Whew, it was quite a day with all the mischief the Leprechaun's left but we all had many good laughs!!!

item.title: march madness
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Let the March Madness begin!!! We spent time last night selecting our brackets. Mitch was very thoughtful in his approach. Mark knew what team he wanted to win and worked backwards from here. His vote, Oregon. I chose based on team names, hip and catchy, winners. I'm going for Zags for the win! Matilda chose based on whoever the 2nd team name was in her two team choices. In the end she chose George Washington because she says it's Obama's team. Oh my!!! Let the madness begin...

item.title: Berkeley
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: We decided to venture into Berkley for the morning. We started out early and spent time soaking in the warm sunshine at an adorable outdoor bakery. Mark and I sipped our lattes while the kids enjoyed a hot cocoa with extra whip and a pastry. It was a wonderful start to the day! Next we toured the campus, went down every pathway, the kids ran down every hill and we took a trip up the the top of the clock tower. The kids loved seeing how far they could see! Then we toured every sports field that we found open as Mitch dreamed about playing sports in college. Matilda ran up every flight of stairs and down every ramp. By lunch the kids were hungry and exhausted. So Mark walked over to Blondie's pizza and brought back a pizza box with yummy-goodness inside. This is Mitch's favorite pizza joint so he was in heaven!!! It was a nice little adventure, soaking up the sun and creating family memories. I loved today.

item.title: april fools
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: We like April Fools in this house. The last few years I've gotten the kids good and had a few good laughs myself. This year the kids counted down the days till April 1st and were scheming with each other to pull off a prank. I wasn't quite prepared for this but I loved that they were getting in to it. I had my tricks planned for weeks, even ran a few trial runs so I was ready for the action! The night before the 1st I strategically placed a trick out for Mark and waited. The next morning he woke up, got ready for work and was gone. No chuckle, no laughter, no you got me, nothing. Darn. Then the kids and I got up, got dressed and had breakfast. We were headed out to camp we learned the car had been relocated down the street. When we finally found the car, there was another prank waiting for us inside... Mark had rearranged all of the seats inside the car. The kids and I got a big laugh out of this prank. In the afternoon, I served the kids a treat. Oreos and milk, one of their favorites. But they weren't thrilled when they found out the oreos were filled with toothpaste!!! Matilda was so angry with me. She threw her cookie down, got out of her chair and ran to her room crying. Oh man... I'm not sure if they'll look at an oreo the same way again!

The four kids, living the life!  It sad to admit that this is the 2nd suite experience for my two and the first for both Mark and I.  How did these kids get so lucky?!! This is how she'd call down to the vendors, shouting through the window, jumping up and down with her finger in the air. The vendors never made it up to the box to deliver but I was suckered in to her sweet attempt every time and would make the trek down to fulfill her order. item.title: star student
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily

item.title: treehouse

item.content:encoded: There are been tree house discussions for over six months in our house. Matilda will sit and sketch out a tree house plan, walk Mark through her plan and the two of them will discuss the architecture of the structure. I'll then give my input on the design but the two of them tell me this is not a project for me to design. Last week, after a discussion over lunch Mark got a new idea for the treehouse. He scanned the area, thought through his plans, the items Matilda envisioned in the treehouse and the next thing I knew he was in the truck, headed to HomeDepot. That afternoon marked the beginning of the treehouse era. This one ladder up against a tree was the start of it all... The kids arrived home and squealed with joy seeing the ladder against the tree. They knew exactly what this meant and couldn't wait to see everything come together. They were such great helpers. They moved wood, carried supplies up and down from the tree, brought Mark water. They were "all in" on this project! Every night we'd spend a few hours outside making a bit more progress on the tree. As each additional piece went up the smiles on the kids faces grew wider. The three musketeers hanging on the platform together! By Friday the house was complete with a railing, a rope ladder, a bucket pulley to pull up snacks and telescope for spotting pirates out in the ocean!!!

item.title: fall
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: After the big Warriors excitement in the tree house, this little girl took a fall. Coming down from the ladder, Matilda lost her footing and fell to the ground. She gave everyone and herself a big scare. After the fall, Matilda was in a lot of pain, found it hard to breath and was complaining of a sore neck. I went in to panic mode feeling something wasn't right. So we made the decision to have someone look at a Matilda to see if she had any broken bones. Our very sweet friend Amy drove Matilda and I to the emergency room to make sure everything was ok while the Dad's stayed home with the boys. Not long after our arrival, the doctor came to see us in the triage room. He did a quick exam on Matilda as she stood stone faced, holding in all the pain. Matilda is so tough I worried she was in a lot more pain that she was letting on. The doctor assured me she'd be ok but will be sore for a few days. After two nights with little to no sleep, Matilda's body finally gave in and decided it needed a rest. We let Matilda sleep in as long as she needed and decided we'd take her to school after she woke up. When I arrived back from doing the first drop off with Mitch, Matilda was cozy in her bed, watching a movie. She was quite happy after her long needed sleep and thrilled with the treat of a movie in her own bed. We are so thankful the fall only resulted in cuts and bruises and a few sore muscles. We all learned the hard way a tough lesson about tree house ladder etiquette.

item.title: rock climbers

Mitchell went first, he didn't get up very high and came right down. The guy told him to give it another go so he went up again, got a bit higher and was smiling when his feet hit the ground. Matilda was next. She flew up the side of the wall almost making it to the top then her hand slipped and down she came. Both smiling from ear to ear they asked to go again. This time they made it higher than their first time up and were quite thrilled of their accomplishments. Mark and I were shocked by their bravery. Nicely done guys!!!

item.title: open house
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Last night the kids invited us to their Open House at school. Mark and I were very excited to see all the hard work the kids put in this last year. Their school is at the end of a very long cul-da-sac so the school arranged for a school bus to pick families up at the local shopping center and shuttle everyone to the school. The kids suggested we take the shuttle bus to add to the adventure of the evening. Little did we know, this was the first time Mark had ever been on a school bus. Who knew an Open House would give us an opportunity as a family to share in one of Mark's first experiences! I told him now knowing this new little fact, I'll sign him up for all future field trips on the bus!!! First we started in kindergarten. All the kids dressed up as pirates and used their map to show us around the classroom. Matilda was so proud of her work. She shared all her writing, math and art with us. She has grown so much throughout the year. I love her confidence and her love for learning. We were really impressed with Matilda's work and enjoyed see all she's accomplished this past year. This photo pulls on my Mama-heart strings. These two are very lucky to be able to participate in each others learning at school. Often times during the year the 1st graders would read to the kindergarten class (Mitch always picked to reach to Tilly!) or the kindergarteners would help the first graders with their class. I love the little bond they have and how much love they have for each other and hope that this special relationship never changes. Then we were off to first grade to see the amazing rainforest that we've heard some much about. There was a checklist of things around the classroom the kids were to share with their parents and we followed that check list to a T. We read looked at every page, read every word and saw every inch of the classroom. These first graders spend a lot of time writing during the day and it shows. One of my very favorite things that Mitch made it his "ME book". He wrote about himself saying he likes football and sports and dislikes getting unhappy faces at school. Boy that is a perfect description of Mitchell! Mitch also wrote about Mark and I and said what our interest were. He was spot on! The story was very sweet and it was so precious to see how proud Mitch was of his accomplishments. Open House 2013

item.title: crazy hair day
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: This week is soccer camp and today is crazy hair day. At the end of each day the coaches give the kids an assignment. When they come to camp the next day they earn points for doing the assignment. The kids with the most amount of points at the end of the week wins something. As with any challenge, our little competitor in the family takes it very seriously, until he heard yesterday it was crazy hair day on Thursday. With such short hair, his creativity options are limited. He came home and said he already lost. But, I wasn't going to let him give up without giving the challenge a go. I wracked my brain all night... think, think, think. Surely we can come up with something good. We can't let this little challenge get us down. Long after the kids had gone to bed I was still thinking. Then it came to me. I sat and leant over to Mark, "we have a popped soccer ball in the garage, what do you think about cutting it to fit Mitch's head, would that work? That could be our take on crazy hair." Mark laughed in disbelief that I was still going on about this in my head but agreed knowing without his agreement I'd be up all night thinking of a new idea. In the morning, after Mitch woke up I pitched my idea to him. He liked the idea but was a little hesitant. I told him to trust me. Per usual in our family, I come up with the hair brained ideas and Mark gets them over the goal line. Today was no different. Mark went into the garage, got the ball, pulled out his pocked knife and worked his magic. In no time Mark had created the perfect hair replacement for Mitch!!! When we got to camp the Coaches were in shock! They said Mitch's hair was the most creative take on crazy hair day they'd ever seen. They even asked if they could take Mitch's picture. Mitch was pretty proud and loved the attention. I walked away smiling. It's times like this I hope he remembers for a long time... when we put our heads together, and take on a challenge as a family, we can come up with something pretty awesome. Good luck in the competition today Buddy... I think your soccer head rocks!!!

item.title: toothless too
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Five years ago just before my sweet little girl turned one, a tiny tooth made it's grand entrance to the bottom of her mouth. That same tooth has been wiggling for months and that same sweet girl has been hoping for that tiny tooth to come out. Today, as Matilda made her way along the diving board to take a flying leap into the pool, she turned back around and came running to tell us her tooth had come out. We were all in disbelief, we thought she was joking with us. But as soon as she opened her hand there it was, the tiny tooth. And as we looked at her smile there was the little hole where that tiny tooth had been living since she was 11 months old. We all cheered and congratulated Matilda on this day finally arriving. She had been patient with that wiggly tooth for quite some time. Mitch also asked to have his photo taken with Matilda since they have now, both lost a tooth. The rest of the evening Matilda spent sticking her tongue through the hole. Bedtime couldn't come soon enough. As she tucked her tooth under her pillow she wished it good luck and said good bye. Matilda told Mark, "I'll always love that little tooth of mine. I'm really gonna miss it when it's gone". Bright and early Saturday morning Matilda sprung out of bed. The tooth fairy had come and she took her tooth and left behind some money. What an exciting time for Matilda. She walked around the house all morning claiming "I got some dollars, I got some dollars".

item.title: Father/Son Basketball Camp
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded:
Meghan decided that we were not busy enough and signed Mitchell and I up for a basketball camp at St. Mary's. It was a great experience, even though my aching muscles tell me that my fitness level needs to be increased. We got to stay in the dorms which Mitch totally loved... (I couldn't tell him we could not afford St. Mary's!) Here is Mitch relaxing for 5 seconds before the first session... Unfortunately not many pictures since it was hard to have the camera out while trying to learn how to dribble a basketball between my legs, spin the ball on my finger, and beat the "NBA wantabees" at buzzer beater. But the experience was amazing. Here is our rough "agenda" for the two days:
  • 12pm -- Checkin We got our rooms and dropped off our bags.. and then we had a few hours to spare before the first session  and 2pm.. OH but I forgot I am with Mitch. We spent the two hours in the gym practicing so we could be ready. He was a great coach, but after two hours of practice I was wondering when the beer break was!
  • Session 1- 2:00pm - 4:30pm OK the session really starts.. the players enter the gym... yes the real players! Wow some are really tall and others are my size.. I am feeling better.. The head coach at St. Mary's takes the floor -- Randy Bennett. He was very inspirational telling us that teamwork and attitude are the most important things he looks for. Next we had Marcus Schroeder lead the session. What a bundle of energy! He took control of the group (My guess around 120 people) We soon learned that if he said "Eyes" we had  to clap our hands twice. Eyes! All in unison we clapped.. complete control in 2 seconds.. pretty impressive! Then the work really started.. we were spit into 8 groups and assigned hoops to practice passing, layups, shooting, defense, etc. By 4:30pm some of us dads were getting pretty tired, some limping going on, a few bloody nails, and lots of aches and pains..
  • Dinner- 4:30pm - 6:00pm What dinner at 4:30 are you mad? Well the kids were super excited to go eat in the cafeteria. Staple dinner for the kids seemed to be fries and ice-cream with some other "side" like hamburger! I couldn't eat much but I can tell you the fries were delicious! As Marcus told us, only place in the world with unlimited soda and ice-cream. Funny I saw Marcus' plate -- salad! Guess I understand his priorities!
  • Session 2- 6:00pm - 8:00pm Another session you have got to be kidding me, where is cocktail hour? This session was more team competition - passing knocking down cones, buzzer beater -- basically 4 sec, 3 sec, 2 sec who could beat the buzzer, dribble tag, ... Pretty tiring, but a lot of fun. We also won an award as the team - best spirit (TEAM 2!). Consequently I lost my voice after that. Sweaty and tired we made it to the end of session 2! (Personal note.. next year I need to train before the event!)
  • Pizza and Movie Night 8:00pm - 10:00pm After a quick shower (oops no towel -- Mitch  learned how to use your shirt to dry!) we were off to the common room to watch a movie. The basketball team bought pizza and beer. The kids loved the pizza, the dad's loved the beer! We then sat down to watch Brian's Song. Very sad movie (thanks guys) which had Mitch asking me questions all night! But we did make it to the end of the movie, and walked back to the dorms.
  • Lights Out 10:30pm I went to sleep at about 10:30pm. I am sure Mitch was still talking to me after I fell asleep.. but the comfy vinyl bed was just great... Zzzzzz
  • Sunday: Wake up 7ish Mitch woke me up at 7am, but we only got out of bed at 7:30 and realized that sharing one shower and toilet with 6 people means scheduling is important. With two almost bursting bladders we got our turn and headed down for breakfast.
  • Breakfast - 8am Back to the cafeteria, and to Mitch's disappointment no ice-cream or fries! Instead eggs, fruit, waffles, cereal, etc.. The cafeteria was packed with another group there as well -- Second Chance -- lots of high school aged kids! After eating a great breakfast it was time for, you guessed it, more basketball.
  • Sunday Session- 9:00am - 12:00pm We were back bouncing the ball, responding to "Eyes" and generally working well in our assigned teams. Mitch was disappointed that "due to dad" we didn't win any awards, but I had a great time. My legs were sore, one ankle a bit tender, knee ache, but all dads made it to 11:00am and then Coach Bennett called all dad's off the court..  "Thank you coach I said to myself" The dad's were off to spend an hour on chalk talk! Coach Bennett went though how he does scouting, how they prepare for a season, how to prepare for a game, and answered a myriad of our questions. What a great session, very insightful. Some key points to me were: - Don't compete recruiting with the Pac12... you will never win! Know what you can offer to whom and compete with where you can! - Attitude counts for everything -- "I would rather lose a game with great guys, than try to win with bad (attitude) guys" - Statistical driven -- for the first 5 weeks of practice every 5 on 5 game is analyzed and points assigned to each player... those with highest points become starters for the season. Everyone knows the system. - Stick with the program -- if you have a winning formula, don't change! While we were having the chalk talk the kids were playing a game. Mitch tells me they won!
  • Awards/Close -- Noon Then we all got back together in the gym and awards were given out. Mitch was very disappointed in our showing, as I mentioned before, apparently one of us just weren't good enough! After this, the fun was all over! What can't we play more?
All in all, this was a fantastic event. I enjoyed every minute of it. The organization, participation, and experience were amazing. Thanks St. Mary's, Coach Bennett, Marcus, and the Basketball team for an amazing time. And to my wife for convincing me to go! ;)

item.title: Family Holiday #2 - travel day
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: It's our favorite time of the year when we pack up the tents and head to the mountains to one of our most favorite camping spots. Last year was the first year we introduced the kids to my childhood camping spot. They had a great time and couldn't wait to go back this year! Packed and ready to go! A request of the kids... Truckee stop for ice cream. We made it. Site #52, our home for the next 8 days! Tent is up and the boys are already relaxing!

item.title: camping day 2
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Today is was cold. After breakfast we packed up the car and headed to Quincy to tour through the town. Matilda was very excited about these plans as one of her favorite books (Winny Fin, Worm Farmer) talks about a little girl who wins first prize at the Quincy County Fair for her worms! Unfortunately, we weren't there when the fair was on and there were no sightings of Winny Fin. We stopped at the local brew pub on our way back to camp for a picnic and a few beers. We played a few rounds of corn-hole and a few games of uno until the clouds rolled in the the rain bucketed down. We quickly packed up and headed for higher ground hoping it would be dry. Once back at camp things looked dry and bright. We set up for cocktail hour and the kids and I made a trip to the showers. Just as we were getting ready to leave, we heard loud thunder and the lights got dim. Before we knew it hail was pounding down on the roof top and covering the round with ice balls. The kids looked outside and asked what we were going to do. Since we weren't prepared for running in the rain we decided to wait the storm out in the bathroom. Ten minutes later the rain grew lighter so we made a run for it only to meet Mark in the pick-up car heading our way to rescue us. Back at camp the stories started about when we were gone my Mom, John and Mark could see the clouds forming but didn't think it was a big deal. Until - it became a very big deal and everything was out uncovered! They tried their best to pull things under the tarp but things were too far gone. We laughed over the stories and enjoyed a few more minutes of cocktail hour until another storm rolled through, this time much closer. My Mom and I grabbed the kids and ran for the car. John and Mark grabbed their cocktails and ran for the car. We sat dry and sheltered for a while watching the hail fill the ground. The kids thought this was the best experience every. The giggles in the back of the car never stopped!!! After the skies settled we checked the site for water damage. My Mom and John's tent was floating in a mud pool. There was mud everywhere and no way of getting inside the tent without bringing the mud in with you. Since our site had wood chips we decided to relocate the tent to allow it to dry out and keep away from the mud! Every day the kids were write in their art journals and draw pictures of our activities so they remember all the fun we had. After today's weather adventures, they had a lot of journal about!

item.title: camping day 3
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Today we woke to blue skies and the sun shining, a nice change following our hail adventures and a night of rain! The wind was blowing which kept the temperatures down so we decided after breakfast we'd pack up and head into Truckee to visit the dinner museum. The kids had a great time at the museum and enjoyed learning about the Donner party and the struggles and hardship the party had while making their way to California. The kids were amazed to see the covered wagons they rode in and couldn't understand how the kids could travel that far, walking. It was fun to see the kids learn about California history and the great questions they had as they pieced the story together and compared it to how they live today. After a nice long picnic at the museum grounds we headed into Truckee for some ice cream. If you're that close to a favorite ice cream place, you have to stop right?! Little did we know, this stop would turn out to be very memorable for us. While enjoying his ice cream Mitch looked down and saw a little red mark on his scoop of vanilla. He felt in his mouth and his loose tooth was gone. He searched the ground but couldn't find it anywhere. How could he lose this tooth? Where did it go? Did he really swallow it? He couldn't believe that would happen. He asked how to get his tooth out to show the Tooth Fairy. We told Mitch we thought leaving a note for the tooth fairy would be fine. He could explain his story and we were sure she'd understand. That night after many games of uno and a great dinner Mitchell got to work on his Tooth Fairy note. Before bed he tucked the note under his pillow and hoped she'd know we were camping and be able to stop by... After a note so cute, who wouldn't understand!

item.title: camping day 4
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: This morning started off very exciting. The Tooth Fairy found us, left money for Mitch's tooth and the note for him to keep. Bonus! But that's not all, the kids also found a frog in the bathroom sing and decided to name it and keep it for their camp pet. They spent quite a long time talking to and caring for the frog and his every need. I don't think the frog himself realized he had so many needs but clearly he did! After the morning events and a bit of breakfast we headed to Portola to the train museum. The kids were all over the place. Up and down every train. Opening and closing every door. Turning every steering wheel. It was exhausting keeping up with them! After loads of fun at the train museum, we headed to Davis Lake for a picnic lunch. Boy was it windy. We could barely stand when we got out of the car. We weren't dressed for the windy weather and decided to drive to where their might be less wind. There Molly went crazy. She rolled in the sand, dashed through the water and brought every stick she could find to Mark. The kids explored the water and the grassy area while my Mom and John watched all the birds flying over. At one point we watched a ground of pelicans land (one by one) in the water (like a sea plan landing) and go under the water for fish. Every few seconds they'd come up and swallow hard to get the fish down their throats! We had a nice, slightly windy lunch then headed back to camp for the late afternoon. Once back at camp my Mom and I took the kids to the park museum to do some gold panning while the boys "rested"! The kids had a great time. Mitchell's strategy mirrored the tactic the miners used - grab a little, swirl it around, get the top of the rocks off and sift through the bottom. Matilda's tactic was more - grab as much as you can and then use your fingers. Both techniques worked well and they each found quite a bit of gold. That evening, back at camp the kids took us hiking to show us the tee-pee they had been building out of sticks. Quite impressive!

item.title: camping day 6
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Today we spent our time chasing the sun. The weather was going to heat up in the afternoon but the clear sky made for a cold start. To keep warm the kids rode their bikes around camp, skipped rope, and found old tree stumps to jump on. In the afternoon we headed to the Kentucky Mine to learn more about the Miners. The tour guide did a really good job retelling the stories from the times which made the tour very enjoyable. Mitch and Mark really loved it. After a special lunch stop to Bassett's Station we left with fully bellies ready to take on the lake. We were shocked at how quiet the lake was. The kids had a great time floating around trying to catch some fish in their net. They each caught a pollywog and were quite thrilled with their netting skills! This is Mark's favorite lake. He always brings his hammock and sets up camp for the afternoon with his pup. Hard life, I know! But it doesn't last long. Soon Mark's hammock is taken over and he's out on the towels! After a fun day at the lake we headed back to camp, cooked dinner, washed dishes and got ready for the camp fire. At the camp fire we sang songs and the kids played the musical instruments. Matilda loved that she got the washboard and wasn't thrilled about switching with anyone.

item.title: camping day 5
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: After a morning touring the museum and the historic houses in Johnsville, we headed back to spend the afternoon at camp. The kids love the river that runs between the campgrounds so we took our bikes and fishing nets and headed to the water for the afternoon. During the first river crossing Mitch slipped and into the cold mountain water he went. He was not thrilled but charged on! The kids found fish swimming under this log. They made many attempts to catch them but the fish were too fast! Soon the kids found this log, or rather "boat" as they called it. They decided if they took the boat out to the fish they'd fool the fish into thinking they were part of the river and then scoop them in their nets. Little did they know, the log rolled in the water when they put their weight on it and soon we had both kids soaking wet up to their shirts. The fun didn't last long as the water was pretty cold but it was funny watching them try to figure out how to make the boat work. And sadly, no fish were every caught during the circus acts!

item.title: camping day 7
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: The theme of the trip this year was "cold mornings". With another frigid wake up, it called for games, books and wrestling in the tent while Mark started a warm fire for us. Then sadly it was time to pack up camp and say our good-byes. The kids completed their tree branch fort while we squeezed everything in the truck. The museum was doing candle making at 11am so Mark and the kids hiked to the museum and Molly and I met them in the car. The kids had heard that I made a candle when I was young that my Mom still has at her house today and were very excited to make their very own own. Round and round the table they went. Once to dip their wick in the wax, then once in the water. We lost count at the number of times they went around but it was a lot. Before we knew it the kids had made two great candles and were very proud of their accomplishments. They were both very sweet and told me I could keep them, which I loved! On our way out, as we said our good-byes we made a stop at the state park sign for our last hurrah! And one last stop at the lake for a shaved ice! Until next year camping... you were great to us!

item.title: Sacramento
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Today was an adventure on the train to Sacramento. The kids loved the train ride and enjoyed eating snacks, playing uno and coloring on the trip. While in Sacramento we toured the Train Museum and enjoyed hearing the stories of how the rails were built, life for families that worked for the railway and traveling the rails. After filling our brains it was time to fill our tummies then walk through old town Sacramento (with a stop of ice cream of course!). Matilda and I had matching glasses for the afternoon! :) During our walk we came upon a team of fire fighters that were doing a training exercise. The Chief was really nice and explained to the kids what they were doing and why and asked if they wanted to sit in the Engine. Of course was their answer! What they didn't anticipate was that they'd be able to put on the headsets and talk to each other in the engine. The kids thought this was the BEST. Through the radio they could also hear other engines talking to the dispatchers. The kids thought hearing the other conversations was a real treat. item.title: new hole

item.title: happy birthday matilda
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Today you turn 6. Deep breath in, deep breath out... How is it you are already 6?! We've been reliving your "birth"day with you a lot lately as you have become very interested in hearing all about the day you were born story. If I close my eyes I remember the day as if it was today. I remember, on that day, making the phone call to the hospital asking if today could be your day. I sit quietly I can feel the silence today of car ride on the way to the hospital. The ride felt like forever - I wondered what you'd look like, what color would your hair be, would you have blue eyes? I wondered what your personality was be like and hoped you'd grow to like your new family. I gazed out the window memorizing every cloud in the sky and can sometimes still feel the warm warm breeze that swept through my hair as we walked from the car to the hospital. I remember waiting very patiently for you to arrive. Completely calm not saying much, just waiting. I remember your Dad watching college football on the TV, enjoying a few chicken strips while passing the time. When I close my eyes I can still hear the muffled football background sounds and smell the chicken. And from there everything else is a blur. What I remember next is after you were born. The nurses picked you up from my arms and wrapped you in the biggest blanket, you were so tiny yet so snug. The blanket was white and it swallowed you. I remember your Dad walking across the room, carrying you in this white blanket. He walked over to the bed and handed you to me and said with the biggest grin "our little girl"... To our little girl Matilda, You sure do make life fun. This last year you have lost two teeth, started reading, never get out of the swimming pool, constantly have duct-tape stuck to your shoes and leave a wake of paper cuttings, marker drawings, block creations, (you name it) behind you when you leave a room. We welcomed a new nickname to your many names this year... "garbage girl". The name was formed from your excessive love for our recycling bin. Your Dad and I know when you have been dumpster diving because there is always little bucket in front of the recycling bin, turned upside down, making the perfect stepping stool for a little girl to see inside. We find further evidence of your dumpster diving, when we walk through the yard and stumble upon a trail of cardboard laying around. We get further confirmation from your dumpster diving when you come flying through the house on your cardboard plane or practically run us over in the kitchen while claiming to be driving into the sunset with your fast cardboard car. Often we get quite a chuckle from your cardboard creations then have remind you, recycling goes out on Tuesday. We're trying our best to scale back on the number of creations piled in the corner of your room, soon the neighbors will think we have a recycling plant inside the house. Most recently, we've had to create a few family cardboard rules; 1) cardboard does not replace clothes for school and 2) no, you can't go down the dirt hill in your cardboard bobsled. You love story time and having books read to you. Anytime we sit on the sofa, there you are with a book asking to read. Often it's the same book or a short few on constant request. Dad has implemented a 'temporary pause' on any books read more than 100 times. He says he needs a little variety in his life and can't take reading "Crafty Chloe" once more. Yet you've gotten so good at memorizing some of your books, you tricked your brother into thinking you learned to read over night. It took quite some time to get you to fess up to your talents! I've seen previews into our future this last year and predict cell phones becoming a big issue in our family. Anything that is square or a small rectangle that fits into the palm of your hands, it's immediately turned into a cell phone. You walk around the house talking on your "phone". You text constantly and often talk longer than your allotted minutes. We are constantly reviewing proper cell phone etiquette - no cell phones at the table, no texting in the bathroom, and when Mom or Dad are talking to you, tell your friends you'll call them back. We don't like talking to you with a phone hanging from one ear! You.don't.sleep. Nighttime is hard for you (or rather, hard for your parents). You've decided it's not fair you have to sleep alone and have declared, on more than one occasion, "I will not close my eyes or sleep at all tonight". You find any excuse to come out of your room. You go the bathroom a million times. You mysterious get aches and pains that only hurt at night. You have the most important things to say, that you can only remember after bedtime. Your blankets are too hot, your pillow is too cold, you can't get comfy and your body simply refuses to sleep (and the list goes on). Evenings are full of surprises and keep your Dad and I quite entertained. Matilda Jay... from the moment you wake up, until the time your body finally fall asleep, you keep us laughing. We love you from the tippy-top of your head, all the way down to the bottom of your toes. The happiest of birthdays to our most favorite six year old!!! -Dad, Mom, Mitchy & Moll-dog

item.content:encoded: Every year we try to attend at least one Cal Bears football game. Mitch and Mark love being in the stands and watching the game. Matilda and I love the cotton candy and chatting with all the people around our seats. This year Cal was playing the Washington Huskies so we knew we needed to attend this game in particular. So Saturday afternoon, we suited the kids up in their Huskies gear and headed out. The sun was shining and skies were clear all the way to the city, we knew it was going to be a good day! First up - the kids were drawn to all the swag handed out along the stadium route. Mitch loves to support breast cancer awareness month and appreciated that all the swag was pink. Matilda loved the cheerleaders. Then it was off to our seats. The visitors section tickets were more expensive than the home team side so we sat amongst the Cal Bears fans, wearing our purple proud! When we got to our seats, what started out as a "go Seahawks" comment to Mitch from the lady sitting in front of us, turned into a get to know you session with one of the chiropractors that work for the Seattle Seahwaks! This nice man showed Mitch his super bowl ring and sweetly agreed to let me take a photo of Mitch with him. How cool is that?! (Mark wished the nice man had let him try the ring on but that didn't happen!) The remainder of the game Mitch's eyes were glued to the field - he stood the entire game, shouting at the players, and expressing his disappointment with some of the ref calls! While Matilda and I made good use of our hand waves to the food vendors and spent time hanging out in the kids zone. It was a fun day for all with the Huskies taking home a win as a bonus!!!

item.title: homework
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Matilda brought home a stack of school work in her folder tonight. As I started to go through it, I noticed the interesting way she identified the work as hers. I said: "Matilda, what is the MH that you write on top your school work?" Matilda: "That's my initials." Me: "I realize that but the paper says name. Last time I checked I don't think I named you MH." Smiling she responds: "Yeah." Me: "What does your teacher say?" Matilda: "Nothing." She's clearly very proud of herself at this stage. I'm stumped. Me: "Lets get in to the habit of writing your name on your assignments where it says name. When it says initials, go ahead and put your initials." Matilda: "Aw, come on Mom!" After Matilda leaves the room I show her work to Mark and make he sees what I see... the MH. His reply? He starts laughing. He's speechless and laughing. I'm missing the funny section of this but one this is certain... clearly Matilda beats to her own drum!

item.content:encoded: After Christmas the kids love to spend a few days quietly playing with their new toys, building new projects, watching new movies, reading new stories and reminiscing about all the excitement the last month has brought.  These quiet days, following the storm, are some of my most favorite days.

item.title: warriors camp
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: Mitch attending Warriors Basketball camp over the Winter break with his best buddy, Wyatt. It was a 3 day camp filled with fun and fitness. Mitch and Wyatt had a great time and were quite tired at the end of the 3rd day! Mitch and Wyatt won the prize for the top 2-2 shooting team!

item.title: new years eve
item.dc:creator: ourfishfamily
item.content:encoded: We had a quiet New Years Eve at home this year. Just the four of us playing games, watching movies and cheering on the ball drop in East Coast from the comfort of our sofa!!! Pouring the bubbly, my kind of guy!!! The highlight of the night was playing minute to win it games. Unfortunately because I was in a complete state of laugher the entire time, we didn't take any photos. I'm not even sure if we made if through the games completely. In true fashion, Mitch was very competitive and got frustrated quickly with the challenges. Matilda on the other hand, stayed focused, stay committed and scored herself the win each time. Mark found creative ways to execute each of the challenges and I laid on the floor laughing the entire time. My what we can learn about ourselves from this experience!!! I'm totally organizing this again for us in the future. Happy New Year... Here's to many exciting things to come in 2015!!!
